"""
mkt-christ — Numbers chapters 11–13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-numbers-11-13.py

Key Christological connections:
- Ch11: Manna/quail → John 6 bread of life; Spirit distributed by reduction vs. Christ
  giving from fullness (John 1:16); Moses's longing for all to prophesy → Pentecost
  (Acts 2/Joel 2); quail judgment → 1 Cor 10:3-6; Moses's unbearable burden → Christ
  who bears all (Matt 11:28-30)
- Ch12: Miriam/Aaron's challenge → Heb 3:1-6 (servant in house vs. Son over house);
  "sees form of YHWH" reversed at transfiguration; el na refa na la → Christ's
  intercession for challengers (Luke 23:34; Heb 7:25)
- Ch13: twelve spies → twelve apostles; Hoshea/Joshua = Yeshua = Jesus; cluster on pole
  → patristic type (Justin Martyr, Tertullian); forty days; Caleb's faith echoes
  Matt 28:18-19; grasshopper self-assessment → 1 Cor 1:27-28
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>The people complained, and YHWH's fire broke out and burned at the edge of the camp. The fire of divine judgment is the first response to Israel's wilderness murmuring — and it is a judgment Christ eventually absorbed on behalf of his people. Luke 12:49 records his own framing: 'I came to cast fire on the earth, and would that it were already kindled!' The fire that judged Israel was the same fire Christ came to bear: on the cross the wrath that burned against human sin was poured out upon him, so that those who had complained against God's provision might be spared (Heb 2:14-15; Gal 3:13).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Moses prayed to YHWH, and the fire died down. Moses's intercessory prayer extinguishes judgment — a pattern running from Exodus 32 to Numbers 14. Christ's intercession is the antitype of every Mosaic prayer for Israel: 'he always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25). Where Moses interceded episodically and the fire would return, Christ's intercession is permanent and its effect is the eternal escaping of wrath for all who draw near to God through him. The fire at Taberah finds its permanent quenching not in Moses's prayer but in the cross.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Taberah (burning) — the site is named for the judgment, a permanent memorial to the fire that broke out. Throughout the Old Testament, place-names record divine judgments as warnings (Kibroth-hattaavah, Massah-Meribah). Christ's death creates a different kind of memorial: not a place named for divine wrath, but a table where bread and wine remember the wrath absorbed, not the wrath imposed. 'Do this in remembrance of me' (Luke 22:19) is the new covenant's Taberah — but it memorializes deliverance from the fire, not destruction in it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The rabble among the people had a strong craving, and wept again: 'Oh that we had meat to eat!' The craving for meat is fundamentally a refusal of grace — YHWH has provided manna, and the people demand something he has not given. Jesus confronted the same dynamic directly: after the feeding of the five thousand, the crowd followed him across the lake wanting more bread, and Jesus reframed the entire encounter: 'Do not work for the food that perishes, but for the food that endures to eternal life' (John 6:27). The rabble's craving for meat is the type of every refusal to receive what God has given in favor of what one wants instead.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'We remember the fish we ate in Egypt that cost nothing — the cucumbers, the melons, the leeks, the onions, and the garlic.' The longing for Egypt's food is a longing for what enslaved them. The memory is nostalgically filtered: the fish 'cost nothing' — forgetting the cost was their bodies and freedom. Christ's confrontation of this same pattern is radical: 'Whoever loves his life will lose it, and whoever hates his life in this world will keep it for eternal life' (John 12:25). The pull toward Egypt's provisions represents the pull toward the world that crucified Christ — a world whose comforts are real but whose costs are ultimate.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'There is nothing at all but this manna to look at.' The manna — a supernatural daily provision that kept Israel alive in a desert — is dismissed as 'nothing.' The contempt for divine provision is at its most explicit here. In John 6, Jesus's audience makes the same dismissal of himself: 'What sign do you do... our fathers ate manna in the wilderness' (John 6:30-31), implicitly demanding something beyond what Jesus offers. And just as the wilderness generation despised the manna that sustained them, many despise the 'plain' gospel of a crucified Messiah: 'the word of the cross is folly to those who are perishing' (1 Cor 1:18). Christ is the manna dismissed as nothing by those who seek more spectacular fare.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Manna described: 'it was like coriander seed, and its appearance like that of bdellium.' The careful physical description of the manna — its color, texture, and origin (the dew) — grounds it as a real provision in the real world, not a symbol. Jesus's claim 'I am the bread of life' (John 6:35, 48) makes the same kind of claim about his own flesh: 'Whoever feeds on my flesh and drinks my blood has eternal life' (John 6:54). The manna is not merely a metaphor for spiritual nourishment — it is actual food that sustained actual bodies. The incarnation follows the same logic: the Word became actual flesh to offer actual salvation for actual human beings.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The people ground the manna and made it into cakes, boiling or baking it. The transformation of manna from dew-given grain into bread through human labor is the ordinary process of cultivation applied to a supernatural provision. Jesus interprets the manna's meaning through the lens of the incarnation: 'The bread of God is he who comes down from heaven and gives life to the world' (John 6:33). Just as the manna came down from heaven and nourished by being received and consumed, Christ came down from heaven and gives life through faith — through receiving him (John 1:12). The grinding and baking of manna anticipates the broken body: 'This is my body, which is broken for you' (1 Cor 11:24).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'When the dew fell upon the camp in the night, the manna fell with it.' The manna arrived with the dew — in the night, quietly, continuously. The provision was never interrupted; every morning it was there. Christ's provision for his people is similarly unceasing: 'I am with you always, to the end of the age' (Matt 28:20); 'he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25). The daily dependability of the manna — never failing, always sufficient — is the type of Christ's uninterrupted mediatorial faithfulness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Moses heard the people weeping throughout their clans, every man at the door of his tent. The grief is corporate, domestic, and pervasive — each family mourning its lack. Christ similarly heard the cries of his people: he wept with those who wept (John 11:35), he was moved with compassion when he saw the crowds (Matt 9:36), and he came not to the healthy but to the sick (Mark 2:17). Where Moses was exhausted and despairing by the people's weeping, Christ's compassion was inexhaustible — 'he is not ashamed to call them brothers' (Heb 2:11) even in their most faithless moments.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Why have you dealt ill with your servant? And why have I not found favor in your sight, that you lay the burden of all this people on me?' Moses's complaint is raw and direct — a protest against the weight of the mediation he has been given. Christ bore the mediation Moses found crushing, not reluctantly but willingly: 'Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest' (Matt 11:28). Where Moses groaned under the burden of the people's complaints, Christ invited the burdened to come to him. The contrast reveals that the weight Moses could not bear was perfectly suited to the one who is simultaneously 'gentle and lowly in heart' (Matt 11:29) and the very Son of God.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Did I conceive all this people? Did I give them birth, that you should say to me, \"Carry them in your arms, as a nurse carries a nursing child, to the land that you swore to give their fathers\"?' Moses's protest denies paternal and maternal connection to the people. Christ's relation to his people is precisely the reverse: he is the one who conceived them in the womb of redemption, who birthed them through his death and resurrection (John 3:3-5; 1 Pet 1:3), and who carries them with a shepherd's tenderness (Isa 40:11 'he will carry them in his bosom'). The bearing Moses refused, Christ chose.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Where am I to get meat to give all this people?' Moses's question exposes the impossible arithmetic of human provision: 600,000 people and nothing to give them. Christ answered this same impossible arithmetic concretely: five loaves and two fish fed five thousand, with twelve baskets left over (Matt 14:17-21). John 6 frames the feeding miracle as the sign of the bread of life — and the disciples' question ('two hundred denarii would not buy enough bread for each of them to get a little,' John 6:7) is precisely Moses's question rephrased. The answer in both cases comes from beyond human provision: from YHWH's abundance, from Christ's authority.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'I am not able to carry all this people alone; the burden is too heavy for me.' Moses's honest admission of limitation sets up the contrast with Christ's invitation: 'Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you and learn from me, for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light' (Matt 11:28-30). The burden that was too heavy for Moses — the mediation of YHWH's grace to an unbelieving people — Christ bears without groaning, and he invites the burdened to find that his bearing is not crushing but life-giving. The yoke he offers is not Moses's yoke but his own.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'If you will treat me like this, kill me at once, if I find favor in your sight, that I may not see my wretchedness.' Moses asks for death as an escape from unbearable responsibility. Christ's death was the opposite: not an escape from the burden of his people but the fullest possible bearing of it — 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree' (1 Pet 2:24). Moses wanted death to end his mediation; Christ's death was his mediation's most complete expression. The one who asked to die rather than continue bearing the people was succeeded by the one whose death was the ultimate bearing of the people's sin.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH told Moses to gather seventy elders to bear the burden with him. The distribution of leadership from Moses to seventy is the OT pattern of expanding the circle of Spirit-enabled leadership — a pattern Christ fulfills when he appoints the Twelve (Mark 3:14-15), then sends out the seventy-two (Luke 10:1, where some manuscripts read 'seventy'). The seventy-two sent out in Luke 10 return with reports of demons submitting (Luke 10:17) — a greater report than Moses's seventy ever gave. The Spirit-distribution that began at the tent of meeting was consummated at Pentecost (Acts 2).</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I will take some of the Spirit that is on you and put it on them.' YHWH's method of endowing the seventy is through redistribution from Moses — the Spirit on Moses is distributed downward, as if from a finite reservoir. Christ's endowment is categorically different: John 1:32-33 records that the Spirit descended on Jesus and remained, and he baptizes 'with the Holy Spirit.' He gives the Spirit not by reduction but from inexhaustible fullness: 'from his fullness we have all received, grace upon grace' (John 1:16). The Spirit on Moses was borrowed from Moses's measure; the Spirit Christ pours out comes from the Son's eternal relationship with the Father and is unlimited.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Consecrate yourselves for tomorrow and you shall eat meat.' The people are called to consecration before the provision — a ritual preparation for receiving YHWH's gift. Christ's body was consecrated before the cross (John 17:19 'for their sake I consecrate myself, that they also may be sanctified in truth') and the Last Supper was the act of preparation: 'Take, eat; this is my body which is broken for you.' The call to consecration before provision anticipates the pattern of the Eucharist, where the community prepares itself to receive the one who was consecrated for them.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'You shall not eat just one day, or two days, or five days, or ten days, or twenty days, but a whole month, until it comes out at your nostrils and becomes loathsome to you.' The abundant provision becomes a curse because it was demanded in unbelief. The same pattern appears in the Psalms (Ps 78:29-31: 'He gave them what they asked, but sent a wasting disease among them') and in Paul's warning: 'God gave them up to their dishonorable passions' (Rom 1:26). Christ's abundant grace is never a curse; what he gives — himself, the bread of life — never becomes loathsome to those who truly receive it (John 6:35 'whoever comes to me shall not hunger and whoever believes in me shall never thirst').</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Because you have rejected YHWH who is among you and have wept before him, saying, \"Why did we come out of Egypt?\"' The rejection of YHWH is the root sin beneath the complaint about food. The same logic governs the rejection of Christ: 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11). The weeping for Egypt is a longing for enslavement over the freedom that YHWH's provision offers — and the rejection of Christ follows the same tragic logic: preferring the slavery of sin to the costly freedom Christ offers (John 8:34-36; Gal 5:1).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Moses doubted: 'The people among whom I am number 600,000 on foot, and you have said, \"I will give them meat, that they may eat a whole month!\" Shall flocks and herds be slaughtered for them, and be enough for them?' Moses's arithmetic of impossibility stands as the type of every human calculation that underestimates divine provision. The disciples performed the same calculation before the feeding of the five thousand: 'Two hundred denarii would not buy enough bread for each of them to get a little' (John 6:7). Both calculations are correct by human math and irrelevant before divine abundance. Christ's feeding miracles are the enacted answer to Moses's doubt — YHWH's provision exceeds every human arithmetic of impossibility.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Shall all the fish of the sea be gathered together for them, and be enough for them?' Moses's rhetorical question about gathering fish anticipates the miracles of Christ. At the Sea of Galilee, Jesus directed the disciples to a miraculous catch so large the nets began to break (Luke 5:6-7; John 21:6). Where Moses considered the sea's fish and saw an impossible supply problem, Christ commanded the fish and they came. 'Is the LORD's hand shortened, that it cannot save? Or his ear dull, that it cannot hear?' (Isa 59:1) — the answer was given in the incarnation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Is the LORD's hand shortened?' The rhetorical question is YHWH's rebuke to Moses's doubt — and the answer is no: the divine arm that brought Israel out of Egypt is not shortened. This becomes a major prophetic phrase (Isa 50:2; 59:1) and Christ's miracles are the definitive answer. When John the Baptist asked whether Jesus was the Coming One or should they expect another, Jesus replied with a catalog of miracles: 'the blind receive their sight and the lame walk, lepers are cleansed and the deaf hear, and the dead are raised up' (Matt 11:4-5) — demonstrating that YHWH's hand is not shortened but gloriously active in the Son.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Moses gathered the seventy elders and set them around the tent, and YHWH came down and spoke to Moses and took some of the Spirit on him and put it on the seventy. The Spirit-transfer at the tent of meeting is the Old Testament's closest anticipation of Pentecost. At Pentecost, the disciples were gathered in one place (the upper room) and YHWH came down (as fire and wind) and distributed the Spirit — not from Moses's measure but from Christ's risen fullness. The tent of meeting is the OT Pentecost; the upper room is the NT fulfillment; Christ is the one from whose fullness the Spirit was poured (Acts 2:33: 'being therefore exalted at the right hand of God, and having received from the Father the promise of the Holy Spirit, he has poured out this that you yourselves are seeing and hearing').</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Spirit rested on the seventy; they prophesied but did not continue doing so. The endowment was temporary — the Spirit rested but did not remain. John 1:32-33 records the contrast explicitly: 'I saw the Spirit descend from heaven like a dove, and it remained on him... He on whom you see the Spirit descend and remain, this is he who baptizes with the Holy Spirit.' The Spirit remaining on Christ — not temporarily resting but permanently dwelling — marks him as the one in whom the full measure of the Spirit lives (Col 2:9 'the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily'). His disciples then receive the permanent indwelling, not the temporary anointing: 'he will give you another Helper to be with you forever' (John 14:16).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Eldad and Medad prophesied in the camp, not having gone to the tent. The Spirit's freedom cannot be institutionally contained — even those not at the designated place received the Spirit and prophesied. Christ made the same point when the disciples tried to stop someone casting out demons in his name: 'Do not stop him, for no one who does a mighty work in my name will be able soon afterward to speak evil of me. For the one who is not against us is for us' (Mark 9:39-40). The Spirit blows where it wills (John 3:8); Pentecost's fulfillment of the Eldad-Medad precedent was the Spirit falling on the Gentiles in Acts 10, surprising the Jewish believers who expected God's activity to follow institutional channels.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A young man ran and told Moses: 'Eldad and Medad are prophesying in the camp.' The report reaches Moses as a potential problem requiring his attention and resolution. The same instinct to report and contain appeared when the disciples told Jesus about the man casting out demons in his name: 'we tried to stop him, because he was not following us' (Mark 9:38). Both the young man at the tent and the disciples with Jesus represent the institutional instinct to police the boundaries of who may work in YHWH's name. Christ's response — like Moses's — refuses to treat Spirit-given activity as requiring official sanction: the criterion is not authorization by the institution but faithfulness to YHWH (or to Christ's name).</p>",
    "28": "<p>'My lord Moses, stop them!' Joshua's protective instinct toward Moses's unique authority is understandable — he is Moses's loyal assistant and does not want the prophetic office cheapened. The same instinct moved the disciples to try to stop the unauthorized exorcist (Mark 9:38) and to rebuke those who brought children to Jesus (Matt 19:13). Christ's response to both gatekeeping instincts was a rebuke: let the children come; do not stop the exorcist. The instinct to protect the authority of the principal by restricting access to his power misunderstands the nature of the kingdom: Christ came not to be protected but to be given, not to restrict the Spirit but to pour it out on all flesh.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Are you jealous for my sake? Would that all YHWH's people were prophets, that YHWH would put his Spirit on them!' Moses's longing for universal prophecy is fulfilled at Pentecost. Peter interprets the Pentecost event explicitly through Joel 2:28-29: 'And in the last days it shall be, God declares, that I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh, and your sons and your daughters shall prophesy' (Acts 2:17). What Moses could only long for — every Israelite as a prophet — Christ achieved for the church and for the world: the Spirit distributed not from Moses's finite measure but from Christ's inexhaustible fullness, poured out on all flesh without exception of sex, age, or social status (Acts 2:17-18).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Moses and the elders of Israel returned to the camp. The movement from the tent back to the ordinary life of the camp marks the rhythm of revelation and return that characterizes OT prophetic activity: ascent to the sacred space, reception of the Spirit, descent to the community. Christ's ministry follows and transcends this pattern: his baptism (the Jordan), his transfiguration (the mountain), his resurrection appearances — all involve sacred moments of divine disclosure followed by a return to the disciples and the world. But where the seventy's endowment was temporary, Christ's permanent glorification means the Spirit he sends to the church does not ebb and return to the tent but abides permanently (John 14:16-17).</p>",
    "31": "<p>YHWH brought quail from the sea and let them fall beside the camp. The abundant quail provision is both miracle and judgment — the prayer for meat is answered, but in a way designed to reveal the corruption at the heart of the craving. Paul uses this episode as a warning to the Corinthians: 'with most of them God was not pleased, for they were overthrown in the wilderness. Now these things took place as examples for us, that we might not desire evil as they did' (1 Cor 10:5-6). Christ's provision is never a judgment in disguise — 'every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom there is no variation or shadow due to change' (James 1:17). The quail abundance was a shadow of the true abundance; the difference is that Christ's self-giving has no admixture of judgment for those who receive it in faith.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The people gathered quail: the least gathered ten homers. The obsessive gathering — beyond any need — reveals the craving's true nature as hoarding rather than satisfaction. Jesus warned against exactly this spirit: 'Do not lay up for yourselves treasures on earth... For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also' (Matt 6:19-21). The manna could not be hoarded (it rotted if kept overnight); the quail could apparently be gathered in unlimited quantity, and the people proved they would gather to their own destruction. Christ's provision of himself is not the quail kind — he cannot be hoarded, manipulated, or consumed to excess; he is received by faith and feeds without destroying.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'While the meat was yet between their teeth, before it was consumed, the anger of YHWH was kindled against the people, and YHWH struck down the people with a very great plague.' Paul cites this moment directly as a warning about the Eucharist: 'whoever eats the bread or drinks the cup of the Lord in an unworthy manner will be guilty concerning the body and blood of the Lord... That is why many of you are weak and ill, and some have died' (1 Cor 11:27-30). The quail that brought death to those who craved wrongly is the OT's warning about consuming sacred provision in the wrong spirit. At the Lord's Table, the same principle applies: Christ's body and blood received in faith bring life; received in self-deception they bring judgment. The plague at Kibroth-hattaavah is the shadow of the sacramental warning.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The site was named Kibroth-hattaavah, 'graves of craving' — a permanent memorial to the plague that killed those whose craving led them from provision into judgment. Memorial names in the wilderness (Taberah/burning, Meribah/quarreling, Kibroth-hattaavah/graves of craving) are the opposite of the memorial Christ institutes: 'Do this in remembrance of me' (1 Cor 11:24). Where the wilderness memorial names remember judgment on craving and complaint, the Eucharistic memorial remembers the gift freely given. The new covenant's memorial is not a grave of craving but a table of grace — the same wilderness setting transformed by the antitype who bore the plague judgment so his people might feast in safety.</p>",
    "35": "<p>From Kibroth-hattaavah to Hazeroth — the journey continues despite judgment. The wilderness narrative has a persistent forward movement: sin, judgment, and then on to the next stage. The failures do not permanently stop the journey. This resilient forward movement is the type of the church's journey through history: the failures of the people of God — their craving, their unbelief, their compromise — do not stop the progress of redemption. Christ's faithfulness carries the journey forward even when the people's faithfulness fails. 'If we are faithless, he remains faithful — for he cannot deny himself' (2 Tim 2:13). The movement from Kibroth-hattaavah to Hazeroth is the movement of grace that does not stop at the graves of human failure.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Miriam and Aaron spoke against Moses because of the Cushite woman he had married. The attack is personal and relational — using his marriage as the entry point for a broader challenge to his authority. Christ likewise faced attacks from religious leaders that used personal details as cover for deeper opposition: the Pharisees and scribes challenged his table fellowship (Mark 2:16), his Sabbath practices (Mark 3:2), his disciples' hand-washing (Mark 7:5). In every case the surface complaint masked the deeper issue: opposition to the one YHWH had appointed as mediator. The challenge to Moses's Cushite wife is the type of every accusation leveraged against YHWH's appointed servant as a proxy for rejecting the servant himself.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Has the LORD indeed spoken only through Moses? Has he not spoken through us also?' The challenge questions the uniqueness of Moses's prophetic office — seeking to relativize it by including Miriam and Aaron as co-equal prophets. Christ's unique mediation was challenged in the same way: 'By what authority are you doing these things, and who gave you this authority?' (Matt 21:23). The Pharisees acknowledged other teachers, other prophets — they denied only Christ's claim to unique, final authority. Miriam and Aaron were legitimate prophets; the challenge was not about their gifts but about whether Moses's office was uniquely authoritative. Christ's answer to his challengers was to demonstrate that his authority came directly from the Father (John 5:19-20; 7:16-17).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Now the man Moses was very humble, more than all people who were on the face of the earth.' The parenthetical note on Moses's humility is the narrator's explanation for why Moses does not defend himself. Christ embodied the same meekness under attack: before Pilate, 'he gave him no answer, not even to a single charge, so that the governor was greatly amazed' (Matt 27:14). The posture of humility under unjust attack — neither self-defense nor retaliation — is simultaneously Moses's characteristic virtue and Christ's defining pattern in the passion. 'I am gentle and lowly in heart' (Matt 11:29) is Christ's self-description; in Moses it is the narrator's assessment; in Christ it is the very nature of the incarnate Son.</p>",
    "4": "<p>YHWH suddenly appeared and summoned Moses, Aaron, and Miriam to the tent of meeting. The divine summoning vindicates YHWH's appointed servant without Moses having to vindicate himself. Christ was vindicated in the same way — not by self-defense but by the Father's testimony. At the baptism: 'This is my beloved Son' (Matt 3:17). At the transfiguration: 'This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased; listen to him' (Matt 17:5). At the resurrection: 'declared to be the Son of God in power according to the Spirit of holiness by his resurrection from the dead' (Rom 1:4). Moses did not need to answer Miriam and Aaron; Christ did not need to answer the Sanhedrin — the Father's vindication was sufficient and decisive.</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH came down in a pillar of cloud and stood at the entrance of the tent, calling Aaron and Miriam to come forward. The pillar of cloud is the form of YHWH's presence throughout the wilderness — the same cloud that guided Israel, covered Sinai, and filled the tabernacle. At Christ's transfiguration, 'a bright cloud overshadowed them, and a voice from the cloud said, \"This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased; listen to him\"' (Matt 17:5). The cloud of divine presence that announced YHWH's judgment on Aaron and Miriam's challenge to Moses becomes the cloud from which the Father vindicates the Son against every challenge. The cloud unites Moses's vindication to Christ's glorification across the wilderness and the mountain.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'If there is a prophet among you, I the LORD make myself known to him in a vision; I speak with him in a dream.' The normal prophetic mode — vision, dream — is characterized by indirectness and mediation: YHWH communicates through symbolic images that must be interpreted. Christ transcended this mode entirely. Heb 1:1-2: 'Long ago, at many times and in many ways, God spoke to our fathers by the prophets, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.' The vision and dream give way to the Son himself — not a mediating image of YHWH but the 'exact imprint of his nature' (Heb 1:3). The prophetic 'if there is a prophet' is surpassed by the incarnational 'the Word became flesh' (John 1:14).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Not so with my servant Moses. He is faithful in all my house.' The description of Moses as 'faithful in all my house' is directly quoted in Hebrews to establish the Moses/Christ typology: 'Moses was faithful in all God's house as a servant, to testify to the things that were to be spoken later, but Christ is faithful over God's house as a Son' (Heb 3:5-6). The distinction is between servant and Son: Moses's fidelity was real, significant, and honorable; Christ's fidelity is categorically greater because the Son stands in a relation to the house that no servant can occupy. Moses's faithfulness authenticates him as the foremost prophet of the Old Testament; Christ's faithfulness authenticates him as the one to whom Moses's entire testimony points.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'With him I speak mouth to mouth, clearly, and not in riddles, and he beholds the form of YHWH.' Moses's unique privilege — seeing the form of YHWH — was the highest the Old Testament offered any human being. At the transfiguration, this relationship is strikingly reversed: Moses appears beside the glorified Christ, who is revealed as the one whose face 'shone like the sun' (Matt 17:2). Moses, who had seen YHWH's form, now stands in the presence of the one whose form reveals YHWH completely. And the Father's voice directs all attention away from Moses (and Elijah): 'Listen to him' (Matt 17:5). The one who spoke mouth to mouth with YHWH is superseded by the one who is YHWH made flesh: 'No one has ever seen God; the only God, who is at the Father's side, he has made him known' (John 1:18).</p>",
    "9": "<p>YHWH's anger burned against them, and he departed. The departure of YHWH's presence is the most severe consequence of challenging his appointed servant — more severe than Miriam's leprosy. When the presence departs, judgment follows. Christ extended this warning in an eschatological register: 'Truly, I say to you, all sins will be forgiven the children of man, and whatever blasphemies they utter, but whoever blasphemes against the Holy Spirit never has forgiveness, but is guilty of an eternal sin' (Mark 3:28-29). The dynamic of opposition to YHWH's appointed mediator leads ultimately to the irrevocable departure of the divine presence — the final judgment that Miriam and Aaron's challenge briefly foreshadowed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>When the cloud removed from over the tent, Miriam was leprous, like snow. Leprosy is the bodily enactment of exclusion — the one afflicted is marked as unclean and separated from the community. Christ healed lepers (Mark 1:40-42; Luke 17:12-19), reversing the direction of the judgment: where Miriam's rebellion produced leprosy, Christ's touch removes it. More profoundly, 2 Cor 5:21 describes Christ becoming sin for us — taking on the condition of spiritual uncleanness so that others might be made clean. Miriam, leprous for her opposition to YHWH's mediator, is the type of the sinner who needs the cleansing touch of the one she opposed.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Aaron said to Moses: 'Oh, my lord, do not punish us because we have done foolishly and have sinned.' Aaron's immediate confession — 'we have sinned' — is the right response to YHWH's judgment. The instinct to turn to Moses as intercessor rather than to YHWH directly reveals Moses's mediatorial role. In the new covenant, Christ is the one to whom sinners turn after their rebellion: 'My little children, I am writing these things to you so that you may not sin. But if anyone does sin, we have an advocate with the Father, Jesus Christ the righteous' (1 John 2:1). Aaron's appeal to Moses against the consequence of his own sin is the type of every appeal to Christ as advocate after the sinner acknowledges guilt.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Aaron pleaded: 'Let her not be as one dead, of whom the flesh is half eaten away.' The vivid description of Miriam's condition makes the full horror of the judgment visceral — it is not a symbolic uncleanness but a bodily death-in-progress. The atonement Christ provides is equally visceral and thorough: 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree, so that we might die to sin and live to righteousness' (1 Pet 2:24). The half-eaten flesh that Aaron describes as the consequence of sin was borne in full by the one who became 'a curse for us — for it is written, \"Cursed is everyone who is hanged on a tree\"' (Gal 3:13). What the law produces in those who rebel against YHWH's mediator, Christ absorbed in his own body.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'O God, please heal her — please' (<em>el na refa na la</em>). The five Hebrew words of Moses's prayer are the most compressed intercessory petition in the Old Testament: direct address (God), urgency (na/please), specific request (heal her), urgency again (na), personal pronoun (la/for her). Moses intercedes for the one who attacked him. Christ does the same from the cross: 'Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do' (Luke 23:34). And his high-priestly intercession continues: 'he always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25). The brevity and urgency of Moses's prayer, offered for an attacker, is the OT shadow of Christ's intercession — which covers not one person for one moment but all his people for all time.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'If her father had but spit in her face, should she not be shamed seven days? Let her be shut outside the camp seven days, and after that she may be brought in again.' The seven-day exclusion is the penalty for being spat on — a severe social shame. The comparison reveals that Miriam's offense (against YHWH, against YHWH's appointed) is no less shameful than a father's severe rebuke. Christ was literally spat upon before his crucifixion (Matt 26:67; 27:30) — bearing the ultimate form of the shame Miriam's exclusion represented. He was 'shut outside the camp' in a different but profounder way: 'Jesus also suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood' (Heb 13:12). He bore the exclusion so that those like Miriam — excluded by their sin — could be brought back in.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Miriam was shut outside the camp seven days, and the people did not set out until she was brought in again. The community's waiting for one member before moving on is a pastoral act — the camp holds for the excluded one. Christ's parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:3-7) encodes the same value: the shepherd leaves the ninety-nine to find the one. The movement of the whole community is held by the condition of one member. The body-of-Christ ecclesiology in 1 Cor 12:26 carries the same logic: 'If one member suffers, all suffer together; if one member is honored, all rejoice together.' The camp waiting for Miriam is the OT type of the church's mutual bearing that Christ established.</p>",
    "16": "<p>After Miriam was healed and restored, the people moved on to the wilderness of Paran. Paran is the staging ground for the spying mission (ch.13) — the movement forward after Miriam's restoration leads directly to the crisis of faith at Kadesh. The pattern is consistent throughout Numbers: restoration, then the next test. Christ's resurrection and the disciples' restoration (Peter's reinstatement at John 21) similarly precede their greatest test and commission: the resurrection appearances lead to Pentecost, and Pentecost leads to the world mission. The wilderness of Paran — the place of the next challenge — awaits those who have been healed and restored. Redemption does not remove the challenge; it equips those who have been restored to face it.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH spoke to Moses: 'Send men to spy out the land of Canaan, which I am giving to the people of Israel.' The land is already given — 'which I am giving' is a completed divine act — and yet human investigation is commanded. The tension between divine certainty and human exploration runs through the entire spy narrative and reaches its crisis in the majority report. Christ sends his disciples on the same pattern: the kingdom is already given ('Fear not, little flock, for it is your Father's good pleasure to give you the kingdom,' Luke 12:32) and yet the disciples are sent to explore and announce it (Matt 28:19). The mission is never about determining whether the land/kingdom is obtainable — it is already given — but about faithfully entering what has been granted.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Send one man from each of their fathers' tribes.' Twelve representatives for twelve tribes — the institutional structure of Israel's covenant community. Jesus appointed twelve apostles for a reason his own saying makes explicit: 'you who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel' (Matt 19:28). The twelve spies sent to represent the twelve tribes are the OT type of the twelve apostles sent to announce the kingdom to the renewed Israel. The structural parallelism is not incidental: the apostles are to the new Israel what the spies were to the old — representatives sent from each community to explore and report on the promised land.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Moses sent them from the wilderness of Paran, according to the command of YHWH. The commission from YHWH through Moses establishes the authority behind the mission. The twelve are not self-appointed explorers; they go because YHWH commanded and Moses authorized. Christ's apostolic commission carries the same double authority: 'As the Father has sent me, even so I am sending you' (John 20:21). The sending of the twelve spies from Paran is the OT prefiguration of the apostolic sending — both grounded in divine command, both structured around representative leadership, both going to explore and claim what YHWH has promised.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The names of the twelve spies begin with Shammua son of Zaccur from Reuben. The list of names records YHWH's chosen representatives from each tribe — a catalog of human beings entrusted with a mission that would determine their generation's fate. Christ chose twelve similarly flawed human beings as his apostles: fishermen, a tax collector, a zealot. The apostolic list (Matt 10:2-4) is the new covenant's answer to the spy list — the same structure of twelve named individuals entrusted with the exploration and proclamation of the promised land. Most of the spies failed; most of the apostles proved faithful after the resurrection. The sending structure endures even when individual recipients fail.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Shaphat son of Hori from Simeon — the representative of Simeon's tribe. In the apostolic parallel, Simon Peter (Simeon, Acts 15:14) becomes the representative of the renewed Israel — the same tribal name taking on new covenant significance. The spy list and the apostle list share not only structure but, in Peter's case, even the name: Simeon/Peter, the one who speaks for the community at critical moments. Where the spy from Simeon joins the majority in faithless report, Simon Peter — after his own failure and restoration — leads the faithful proclamation at Pentecost (Acts 2:14-36).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Caleb son of Jephunneh from Judah — the spy who brings the faithful minority report alongside Joshua. The tribe of Judah is the tribe of the Messiah (Gen 49:10; Rev 5:5), and Caleb, Judah's representative, is the spy of exceptional faith. His report — 'we are well able to overcome it' (v.30) — is the one that aligns with YHWH's promise. Christ, the Lion of Judah, embodies Caleb's faith in its fullest expression: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore...' (Matt 28:18-19). The Judahite spy who believed YHWH's promise foreshadows the Judahite Son who is the promise embodied.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Igal son of Joseph from Issachar — the tribe's representative among the twelve. The expansion of YHWH's covenant community to include all twelve tribes is the OT type of the gospel's extension to all nations. Just as twelve tribal representatives were sent together on one mission, Christ sends his apostles together with one commission: 'make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:19). The tribal diversity of the spy mission — twelve different lineages united by one commission — is the structural template for the missionary church, which gathers from every tribe and nation (Rev 5:9) without losing its common commission.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Hoshea son of Nun from Ephraim — the one whom Moses will rename. The name Hoshea (הוֹשֵׁעַ, salvation/he saves) already contains the salvific root; it is the abbreviated form of the name Moses will expand. Hoshea's identity, and the entire salvation it points to, awaits the renaming that will make explicit what the name implies. In the same way, Israel's long narrative of salvation-acts — the exodus, the wilderness provision, the conquest — awaited the one whose name would make explicit what all the preceding acts of YHWH implied: 'you shall call his name Jesus (Yeshua), for he will save his people from their sins' (Matt 1:21). Hoshea is already a salvation-name, but the full weight of that name awaits Moses's act of renaming.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Palti son of Raphu from Benjamin — Benjamin, the tribe from which Saul came and from which Paul the apostle descended (Rom 11:1; Phil 3:5). The Benjaminite spy who was sent from the smallest tribe represents the same community from which YHWH would later call Paul, the apostle to the Gentiles. The smallest tribe, the last-born son's tribe, provides the most improbable missionary: 'God chose what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not, to bring to nothing things that are' (1 Cor 1:28). The Benjaminite in the spy list is a distant foreshadowing of the Benjaminite apostle who would carry the good news of the true promised land to the ends of the earth.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Gaddiel son of Sodi from Zebulun — Zebulun, the tribe that inhabited the Galilee region, the land of shadows (Isa 9:1-2: 'The land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali... the people dwelling in darkness have seen a great light'). Matthew's Gospel opens Christ's ministry by fulfilling this prophecy (Matt 4:13-16): Jesus made his home in Zebulun's territory and from there began to proclaim the kingdom. The spy from Zebulun who went to explore the land of Canaan is a shadow of the one who came from Zebulun's own territory — not to spy out a human promise but to inaugurate the fulfillment of every promise in his own person.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gaddi son of Susi from Manasseh — the tribe of the half-portion, Joseph's first son. Manasseh, like Ephraim, received the full tribal inheritance through Jacob's reversal of birth-order blessing (Gen 48:14-20). The dividing of Joseph's inheritance between his two sons and the inclusion of both in the twelve is itself a type of the gospel's inclusion of the unexpected: those who were not first in birth order receive the full inheritance. Christ's own reversal of expected priorities — 'the last shall be first' (Matt 20:16), 'unless you turn and become like children' (Matt 18:3) — follows the logic of the Manasseh/Ephraim reversal that gave the younger the greater blessing.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Ammiel son of Gemalli from Dan — from the northernmost tribe, the one that would later set up idols at Laish/Dan (Judg 18:30). Dan's representative among the twelve spies is a reminder that even those from tribes later notorious for apostasy were given the same mission, the same commission, the same opportunity. Christ called Judas Iscariot to be one of the twelve despite knowing what he would do (John 6:64) — the mission-structure includes the unfaithful without being determined by them. The apostolic commission is not nullified by individual defection; the structure of the twelve persists even when individual members fail (Acts 1:15-26).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Sethur son of Michael from Asher — from the tribe whose territory included the Phoenician coast. Asher's blessing in Gen 49:20 and Deut 33:24-25 emphasized abundance: 'his food shall be rich, and he shall yield royal delicacies.' The spy from the tribe of abundance goes to see whether the land is rich or poor (v.20). What he sees is literally true — the land does flow with milk and honey (v.27) — but the majority's fear overcomes the abundance. Christ's promise to his disciples also involves abundance: 'I came that they may have life and have it abundantly' (John 10:10). The failure of the spy from Asher to embrace the abundance he was sent to explore is the type of every refusal of the abundant life Christ offers because of fear of the cost.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Nahbi son of Vophsi from Naphtali — Naphtali, the other tribe of the northern Galilee region (Isa 9:1). Like Zebulun, Naphtali was the territory of 'people dwelling in darkness' who 'have seen a great light.' The spy from Naphtali was sent to see whether the promised land held light or darkness, abundance or deprivation. Christ's proclamation from Zebulun and Naphtali's territory answered the question the spies could not answer faithfully: the kingdom of heaven — the true promised land — has arrived, and those who were in the deepest darkness are the first to receive the light (Matt 4:13-17). The darkness of the spy narrative is dispelled by the light that Naphtali's territory would one day see.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Geuel son of Maki from Gad — Gad, the tribe that would later choose the east bank of the Jordan (Num 32:1-5) and received a conditional inheritance. The spy from Gad goes to explore the promised land that his tribe would later choose not to fully inhabit. The partial inheritance of the east-bank tribes anticipates the incomplete entry that characterizes the entire generation: even those who were sent to explore and were willing to enter did not always claim the full inheritance. Christ warns against the same pattern: 'No one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God' (Luke 9:62). The incomplete entry, the conditional inheritance, the looking back toward the east bank — all are warnings against partial commitment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'These are the names of the men whom Moses sent to spy out the land. And Moses called Hoshea the son of Nun Joshua.' The renaming is the hinge of the entire passage. Hoshea (יְהוֹשֻׁעַ abbreviated: הוֹשֵׁעַ) becomes Joshua (יְהוֹשֻׁעַ) — 'YHWH is salvation.' This is the same name as Jesus: the Greek Ἰησοῦς (Iēsous) transliterates the Hebrew Yeshua/Joshua. Heb 4:8-11 directly contrasts Joshua and Christ: Joshua brought Israel into the earthly rest, but if that rest had been complete, YHWH would not have spoken through David of another rest still to come. Therefore the Joshua who gives rest is a type of the Jesus/Yeshua who gives the true rest that Joshua could only shadow. The renaming is a Messianic act: Moses gives the mission's representative the name that belongs fully only to the one who truly saves his people.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Go up into the Negeb and go up into the hill country, and see what the land is, and whether the people who dwell in it are strong or weak.' The reconnaissance mission requires courage — going into the land of formidable opponents to assess the situation clearly. Jesus sends his disciples on the same kind of mission: 'Behold, I am sending you out as sheep in the midst of wolves, so be wise as serpents and innocent as doves' (Matt 10:16). Clear-eyed assessment of danger, combined with faithful trust in the sender, is the posture Christ commands. The failure of the ten spies was not in accurately seeing the strength of the Canaanites but in allowing what they accurately saw to override what YHWH had promised.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And see what the land is, and whether the people who dwell in it are strong or weak, whether they are few or many.' The mission is one of reconnaissance for faithful entry, not for timid hesitation. Every strategic fact they are sent to gather is meant to inform courage, not undermine it — YHWH has already said 'I am giving this land to you,' so the question 'are they strong or weak?' is a question about what obstacles faith will need to overcome, not whether faith is warranted. Christ sends his disciples with the same foreknowledge of obstacles: 'You will be hated by all for my name's sake' (Matt 10:22). Knowing the opposition in advance is not an argument against the mission but preparation for faithful execution of it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'And whether the land that they dwell in is good or bad, and whether the cities that they dwell in are camps or strongholds.' The thorough investigation covers everything from the land's quality to the nature of its settlements. Christ commends the same thoroughness in kingdom work: 'What king, going out to encounter another king in war, will not sit down first and deliberate whether he is able with ten thousand to meet him who comes against him with twenty thousand?' (Luke 14:31). Faithful mission is informed mission; the willingness to face reality clearly — the strongholds and the fortified cities — is not a failure of faith but a preparation for courageous obedience. The failure of the spies was not their investigation but their response to what they found.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And whether the land is rich or poor, and whether there are trees in it or not. Be of good courage and bring some of the fruit of the land.' The command 'be of good courage' (<em>hithchazaqtem</em>) is the standing command for every wilderness mission: it appears at Moses's commissioning of Joshua (Deut 31:7-8), at YHWH's commissioning of Joshua (Josh 1:6-9), and at Christ's commissioning of his disciples: 'In the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world' (John 16:33). The fruit of the land they are commanded to bring is the evidence of the promise's reality — and the enormous cluster of grapes (v.23) becomes the most significant exhibit. Jesus commands his disciples to bear fruit (John 15:8) — tangible evidence of the kingdom's reality.</p>",
    "21": "<p>They went up and spied out the land from the wilderness of Zin to Rehob, near the entrance to Hamath — a comprehensive survey from south to north. The fullness of the survey reflects the fullness of the commission: not partial investigation but comprehensive exploration of everything YHWH was giving. Christ's commission to his disciples is similarly comprehensive: 'all nations' (Matt 28:19), 'to the end of the earth' (Acts 1:8), 'every creature' (Mark 16:15). The scope of the spy mission — the whole land — corresponds to the scope of the apostolic mission — the whole world. Both missions are given to human beings who will fail to comprehend the full scope of what they are sent into, but the comprehensiveness of the commission establishes the goal.</p>",
    "22": "<p>They came to Hebron, where Ahiman, Sheshai, and Talmai, the descendants of Anak, lived — Hebron was built seven years before Zoan in Egypt. The mention of Hebron grounds the narrative in specific, verifiable geography: Hebron was Abraham's burial place (Gen 23:2-19), the first piece of Canaan Abraham owned, a site of YHWH's covenant promises. The giants who now occupied it were usurpers of what had been covenanted to Israel. Christ, entering a world occupied by opposing powers, similarly entered territory that belonged to his Father: 'The earth is the LORD's and the fullness thereof' (Ps 24:1). The gospel mission is a reclamation, not an invasion — going into territory that YHWH owns and that the powers of darkness occupy illegitimately (Col 2:15; Heb 2:14-15).</p>",
    "23": "<p>They came to the Valley of Eshcol and cut from there a branch with a single cluster of grapes, so large it took two men to carry it on a pole between them. Justin Martyr (<em>Dialogue with Trypho</em> 86) and Tertullian (<em>Against Marcion</em> 3.18) identified this as a type of the crucifixion: the cluster (Christ, the true vine, John 15:1) hung on wood (the pole/cross) between two men (the two thieves), carried by those who did not understand what they were transporting. The fruit of the promised land — the abundance that the mission was sent to discover — is a single massive cluster: Christ himself is the totality of what the promised land was pointing toward, the true 'fruit of the vine' (Matt 26:29) that will be drunk new in the Father's kingdom.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The place was called the Wadi of Eshcol (cluster), because of the cluster that the people of Israel cut down from there. Named for the fruitfulness — the valley named by the fruit it yielded. The new covenant names its central assembly practice for the same fruitfulness: the Eucharist takes its name from thanksgiving (<em>eucharistia</em>) for the gift given, just as the valley was named for the cluster received. The abundance of the promised land — one cluster requiring two men — is the abundance Christ promises to those who bear fruit for him: 'Whoever abides in me and I in him, he it is that bears much fruit' (John 15:5). The Eshcol cluster is the OT type of Eucharistic abundance — a single gift that exceeds what the recipients could have imagined.</p>",
    "25": "<p>At the end of forty days they returned from spying out the land. The forty days of the spy mission links explicitly to the wilderness generation's forty-year judgment: 'a year for each day, forty days, forty years' (Num 14:34). But the forty days point forward as well as backward: Christ's forty days of testing in the wilderness (Matt 4:2) recapitulate Israel's forty-year testing, succeeding where Israel failed. And the forty days of post-resurrection appearances (Acts 1:3) are the counterpart to the forty days of the spy mission — where the spies returned with a report that led to forty years of judgment, Christ's forty post-resurrection days prepared his disciples for a mission that would succeed where the spies' mission failed.</p>",
    "26": "<p>They came back to Moses and Aaron and to all the congregation of the people of Israel in the wilderness of Paran and brought back word to them and to all the congregation, and showed them the fruit of the land. The return and report is a moment of testimony — the spies bring back both the word (verbal report) and the evidence (the fruit). The pattern of apostolic testimony in the NT follows the same structure: the eyewitnesses report what they saw and heard (1 John 1:1-3; 2 Pet 1:16-18) and present evidence (the transformed lives of converts; the miracles of the Spirit). The fruit the spies brought back was the most tangible proof that the promised land was real; Christ's resurrection is the most tangible proof that the kingdom is real (1 Cor 15:20: 'the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep').</p>",
    "27": "<p>'We came to the land to which you sent us. It flows with milk and honey, and this is its fruit.' The honest opening of the majority report — the land is everything YHWH said it was. The kingdom Christ announces is similarly what it appears to be: real, abundant, and worth everything. The parables of the kingdom (Matt 13:44-46) describe a treasure worth selling everything to obtain. The spies who acknowledged the land's richness before letting their fear override them had the right data; their failure was in allowing the size of the opposition to overwhelm the size of the promise. Christ's disciples face the same temptation: to acknowledge that the kingdom is real and then act as if it were not worth the cost of entry.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'However, the people who dwell in the land are strong, and the cities are fortified and very large. And besides, we saw the descendants of Anak there.' The 'however' is the hinge on which the majority report turns — from accurate report to faithless conclusion. In the life of discipleship, the 'howevers' are the obstacles that faith must overcome rather than surrender to: 'In the world you will have tribulation' (John 16:33), 'you will be dragged before kings and governors for my name's sake' (Matt 10:18). The fortified cities and the Anakites are real obstacles to real mission — Christ does not deny the 'howevers' of opposition but inverts their weight: 'take heart; I have overcome the world' (John 16:33). The 'however' does not end the mission; the 'I have overcome' does.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Amalekites dwell in the land of the Negeb. The Hittites, the Jebusites, and the Amorites dwell in the hill country. The Canaanites dwell by the sea and along the Jordan. The catalogue of peoples maps the opposition comprehensively — every direction, every terrain, every people-group has formidable inhabitants. The NT mission encounters a similarly comprehensive opposition: 'For we do not wrestle against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the authorities, against the cosmic powers over this present darkness, against the spiritual forces of evil in the heavenly places' (Eph 6:12). The spy mission's comprehensive enemy catalogue corresponds to the apostolic awareness of comprehensive spiritual opposition — which makes the comprehensiveness of Christ's authority ('all authority in heaven and on earth,' Matt 28:18) the decisive answer.</p>",
    "30": "<p>But Caleb quieted the people before Moses and said, 'Let us go up at once and occupy it, for we are well able to overcome it.' Caleb's faith-response is the OT antecedent of the commission Christ gives after announcing his authority: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Go therefore...' (Matt 28:18-19). The movement from 'we are well able' to 'go therefore' follows exactly the same logic: the ability does not rest on the humans' own strength but on the one who sends them. Caleb's confidence was grounded in YHWH's promise ('he will bring us into this land,' 14:8); Christ's disciples' confidence is grounded in Christ's authority. The 'we are well able' of Caleb becomes the 'go therefore' of the Great Commission — both resting on the power of the sender, not the competence of the sent.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'We are not able to go up against the people, for they are stronger than we are.' The majority's conclusion is a straightforward calculation of human strength: us vs. them, and they win. This is the logic that every generation of disciples must resist. Peter's sinking in the water (Matt 14:30) was the same calculation: the wind was strong, Peter was ordinary. Christ's rebuke — 'O you of little faith, why did you doubt?' — is the same rebuke implicit in YHWH's response to the majority report. The question is never whether the opposition is stronger than the disciples; it always is. The question is whether the disciples are trusting in the strength of the one who sends them or calculating their own strength against the enemy's.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'The land, through which we have gone to spy it out, is a land that devours its inhabitants, and all the people that we saw in it are of great height.' The majority report's characterization of the land as 'devouring its inhabitants' is a rhetorical exaggeration driven by fear — inverting the actual report (the land flows with milk and honey, v.27) into its opposite. Fear always inverts reality: it makes the gift look like a threat and the threat look insurmountable. Christ identifies this inversion and names it: 'Why are you afraid, O you of little faith?' (Matt 8:26). The disciples on the sea saw the waves and concluded they were perishing; they did not see that they were in the boat with the one who commands wind and waves. The land that devours was actually a land given — the spies' inversion was the inversion of unbelief.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'And there we saw the Nephilim (the sons of Anak, who come from the Nephilim), and we seemed to ourselves like grasshoppers, and so we seemed to them.' The grasshopper self-assessment is one of Scripture's most memorable images of faithless self-perception — comparing oneself to the enemy rather than looking to YHWH. The problem is not that the spies were small; the problem is that they measured themselves against the Anakites rather than measuring the Anakites against YHWH. Paul's counterpart is 1 Cor 1:27-28: 'God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong; God chose what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not, to bring to nothing things that are.' Christ himself was despised and of no account (Isa 53:3) — the one who looked most like a grasshopper before the powers of the world was the one who disarmed the principalities and powers and put them to open shame (Col 2:15).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('christ', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(existing, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('christ', 'numbers', existing)
    total = sum(len(existing.get(ch, {})) for ch in ['11','12','13'])
    print(f'ch 11-13: {total} verses in output')
    print('Numbers 11-13 christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
